e/erlebnis-schloss-garten/schloss-garten/gebaeude/festsaele/|publisher=Staatliche Schl\u00f6sser und G\u00e4rten Baden-W\u00fcrttemberg|accessdate=11 July 2018|ref={{sfnref|Bruchsal Palace: Fest\u00e4le}}}}\n* {{cite web|title=Das S\u00fcdliche Staatsappartement|url=https://www.schloss-bruchsal.de/erlebnis-schloss-garten/schloss-garten/gebaeude/die-beletage/das-suedliche-staatsappartement/|publisher=Staatliche Schl\u00f6sser und G\u00e4rten Baden-W\u00fcrttemberg|accessdate=11 July 2018|ref={{sfnref|Bruchsal Palace: S\u00fcdliche Staatsappartement}}}}\n* {{cite web|title=Das N\u00f6rdliche Staatsappartement|url=https://www.schloss-bruchsal.de/erlebnis-schloss-garten/schloss-garten/gebaeude/die-beletage/das-noerdliche-staatsappartement/|publisher=Staatliche Schl\u00f6sser und G\u00e4rten Baden-W\u00fcrttemberg|accessdate=23 March 2019|ref={{sfnref|Bruchsal Palace: N\u00f6rdliche Staatsappartement}}}}\n* {{cite web|title=F\u00fcrstbisch\u00f6fliche Privatr\u00e4ume|url=https://www.schloss-bruchsal.de/erlebnis-schloss-garten/schloss-garten/gebaeude/die-beletage/fuerstbischoefliche-privatraeume/|publisher=Staatliche Schl\u00f6sser und G\u00e4rten Baden-W\u00fcrttemberg|accessdate=24 March 2019|ref={{sfnref|Bruchsal Palace: F\u00fcrstbisch\u00f6fliche Privatr\u00e4ume}}}}\n* {{cite web|title=Das Appartement der Amalie von Baden|url=https://www.schloss-bruchsal.de/erlebnis-schloss-garten/schloss-garten/gebaeude/die-beletage/das-appartement-der-amalie-von-baden/|publisher=Staatliche Schl\u00f6sser und G\u00e4rten Baden-W\u00fcrttemberg|accessdate=24 March 2019|ref={{sfnref|Bruchsal Palace: Appartement der Amalie von Baden}}}}\n* {{cite web|title=Die Hofkirche|url=https://www.schloss-bruchsal.de/erlebnis-schloss-garten/schloss-garten/gebaeude/hofkirche/|publisher=Staatliche Schl\u00f6sser und G\u00e4rten Baden-W\u00fcrttemberg|accessdate=11 July 2018|ref={{sfnref|Bruchsal Palace: Hofkirche}}}}\n* {{cite web|title=Der Garten|url=http://www.schloss-bruchsal.de/erlebnis-schloss-garten/schloss-garten/garten/|publisher=Staatliche Schl\u00f6sser und G\u00e4rten Baden-W\u00fcrttemberg|accessdate=11 July 2018|ref={{sfnref|Bruchsal Palace: Der Garten}}}}\n\n* {{cite web|title=Das Laubenzimmer|url=https://www.schloss-bruchsal.de/erlebnis-schloss-garten/verborgene-schaetze/laubenzimmer/|publisher=Staatliche Schl\u00f6sser und G\u00e4rten Baden-W\u00fcrttemberg|accessdate=11 July 2018|ref={{sfnref|Bruchsal Palace: Laubenzimmer}}}}\n* {{cite web|title=Das Deckenfresko|url=https://www.schloss-bruchsal.de/erlebnis-schloss-garten/verborgene-schaetze/deckenfresko/|publisher=Staatliche Schl\u00f6sser und G\u00e4rten Baden-W\u00fcrttemberg|accessdate=11 July 2018|ref={{sfnref|Bruchsal Palace: Deckenfresko}}}}\n* {{cite web|title=Der Kammermusiksaal|url=https://www.schloss-bruchsal.de/erlebnis-schloss-garten/verborgene-schaetze/kammermusiksaal/|publisher=Staatliche Schl\u00f6sser und G\u00e4rten Baden-W\u00fcrttemberg|accessdate=11 July 2018|ref={{sfnref|Bruchsal Palace: Kammermusiksaal}}}}\n* {{cite web|title=Tapisserien|url=https://www.schloss-bruchsal.de/erlebnis-schloss-garten/verborgene-schaetze/tapisserien/|publisher=Staatliche Schl\u00f6sser und G\u00e4rten Baden-W\u00fcrttemberg|accessdate=29 January 2019|ref={{sfnref|Bruchsal Palace: Tapisserien}}}}\n\n* {{cite web|title=Ausstellungen|url=https://www.schloss-bruchsal.de/erlebnis-schloss-garten/ausstellungen/|publisher=Staatliche Schl\u00f6sser und G\u00e4rten Baden-W\u00fcrttemberg|accessdate=11 July 2018|ref={{sfnref|Bruchsal Palace: Ausstellungen}}}}\n\n* {{cite web|title=Stilgeschichte|url=https://www.schloss-bruchsal.de/wissenswert-amuesant/stilgeschichte/|publisher=Staatliche Schl\u00f6sser und G\u00e4rten Baden-W\u00fcrttemberg|accessdate=11 July 2018|ref={{sfnref|Bruchsal Palace: Stilgeschichte}}}}\n\n* {{cite web|title=Damian Hugo von Sch\u00f6nborn|url=https://www.schloss-bruchsal.de/wissenswert-amuesant/persoenlichkeiten/damian-hugo-von-schoenborn/|publisher=Staatliche Schl\u00f6sser und G\u00e4rten Baden-W\u00fcrttemberg|accessdate=30 January 2019|ref={{sfnref|Bruchsal Palace: Damian Hugo von Sch\u00f6nborn}}}}\n* {{cite web|title=Franz Christoph von Hutten|url=https://www.schloss-bruchsal.de/wissenswert-amuesant/persoenlichkeiten/franz-christoph-von-hutten/|publisher=Staatliche Schl\u00f6sser und G\u00e4rten Baden-W\u00fcrttemberg|accessdate=30 January 2019|ref={{sfnref|Bruchsal Palace: Franz Christoph von Hutten}}}}\n* {{cite web|title=Architeckt Balthasar Neumann|url=https://www.schloss-bruchsal.de/wissenswert-amuesant/persoenlichkeiten/architekt-balthasar-neumann/|publisher=Staatliche Schl\u00f6sser und G\u00e4rten Baden-W\u00fcrttemberg|accessdate=30 January 2019|ref={{sfnref|Bruchsal Palace: Architekt Balthasar Neumann}}}}\n\n* {{cite web|title=S\u00e4kularisation in Bruchsal|url=https://www.schloss-bruchsal.de/wissenswert-amuesant/dossiers/saekularisation-in-bruchsal/|publisher=Staatliche Schl\u00f6sser und G\u00e4rten Baden-W\u00fcrttemberg|accessdate=11 July 2018|ref={{sfnref|Bruchsal Palace: S\u00e4kularisation}}}}\n* {{cite web|title=Das Ende der Monarchie|url=https://www.schloss-bruchsal.de/wissenswert-amuesant/dossiers/das-ende-der-monarchie/|publisher=Staatliche Schl\u00f6sser und G\u00e4rten Baden-W\u00fcrttemberg|accessdate=30 January 2019|ref={{sfnref|Bruchsal Palace: Das Ende der Monarchie}}}}\n* {{cite web|title=Zerst\u00f6rung und Wiederaufbau|url=https://www.schloss-bruchsal.de/wissenswert-amuesant/dossiers/zerstoerung-und-wiederaufbau/|publisher=Staatliche Schl\u00f6sser und G\u00e4rten Baden-W\u00fcrttemberg|accessdate=11 July 2018|ref={{sfnref|Bruchsal Palace: Zerst\u00f6rung und Wiederaufbau}}}}\n* {{cite web|title=Mitterand und Kohl|url=https://www.schloss-bruchsal.de/wissenswert-amuesant/dossiers/mitterand-und-kohl/|publisher=Staatliche Schl\u00f6sser und G\u00e4rten Baden-W\u00fcrttemberg|accessdate=24 March 2019|ref={{sfnref|Bruchsal Palace: Mitterand und Kohl}}}}\n\n* {{cite web|title=Sch\u00f6nborn und der Maler|url=https://www.schloss-bruchsal.de/wissenswert-amuesant/anekdoten/schoenborn-und-der-maler/|publisher=Staatliche Schl\u00f6sser und G\u00e4rten Baden-W\u00fcrttemberg|accessdate=11 July 2018|ref={{sfnref|Bruchsal Palace: Sch\u00f6nborn und der Maler}}}}\n* {{cite web|title=F\u00fcrstliche Langeweile|url=https://www.schloss-bruchsal.de/wissenswert-amuesant/anekdoten/fuerstliche-langeweile/|publisher=Staatliche Schl\u00f6sser und G\u00e4rten Baden-W\u00fcrttemberg|accessdate=11 July 2018|ref={{sfnref|Bruchsal Palace: F\u00fcrstliche Langeweile}}}}\n* {{cite web|title=Das Verlassene Schloss|url=https://www.schloss-bruchsal.de/wissenswert-amuesant/anekdoten/verlassenes-schloss/|publisher=Staatliche Schl\u00f6sser und G\u00e4rten Baden-W\u00fcrttemberg|accessdate=11 July 2018|ref={{sfnref|Bruchsal Palace: Verlassene Schloss}}}}\n{{refend}}\n\n;City of Bruchsal (in German)\n{{refbegin|25em}}\n* {{cite web|title=St\u00e4dtisches Museum im Barockschloss Bruchsal|url=https://www.bruchsal.de/,Lde/Home/Touristik+_+Kultur/Staedtisches+Museum+im+Barockschloss+Bruchsal.html|website=bruchsal.de|accessdate=10 October 2018|ref={{sfnref|City of Bruchsal: St\u00e4dtisches Museum}}}}\n* {{cite web|title=Schloss Bruchsal|url=https://www.bruchsal.de/,Lde,(anker507434)/Home/Touristik+_+Kultur/Schloss+Bruchsal.html#anker507434|website=bruchsal.de|accessdate=30 January 2019|ref={{sfnref|City of Bruchsal: Schloss Bruchsal}}}}\n* {{cite web|title=DIGA - Die Gartenmesse|url=https://www.bruchsal.de/site/Bruchsal-Internet/node/492176/Lde/zmdetail_1722489/DIGA_Die_Gartenmesse.html?zm.sid=zm3cujkj1u51&nodeID=1722489|website=bruchsal.de|accessdate=29 January 2019|ref={{sfnref|City of Bruchsal: DiGA - Die Gartenmesse}}}}\n{{refend}}\n\n;Baden State Museum (in German)\n{{refbegin|25em}}\n* {{cite web|title=Die Sammlungsausstellung: Deutsches Musikautomaten-Museum|url=http://www.landesmuseum.de/website/Deutsch/Sammlungsausstellungen/Deutsches_Musikautomaten-Museum/Ausstellung.htm|accessdate=10 October 2018|ref={{sfnref|Baden State Museum: Deutsches Musikautomaten-Museum}}}}\n* {{cite web|title=Musikautomaten-Galerie|url=http://www.landesmuseum.de/website/Deutsch/Sammlungsausstellungen/Deutsches_Musikautomaten-Museum/Musikautomaten-Galerie.htm|accessdate=10 October 2018|ref={{sfnref|Baden State Museum: Musikautomaten-Galerie}}}}\n* {{cite web|title=Die Titanic-Orgel|url=http://landesmuseum.de/website/Deutsch/Sonderausstellungen/Rueckblick/2012/Die_quot_Titanic-Orgel_quot_.htm|accessdate=10 October 2018|ref={{sfnref|Baden State Museum: Die \"Titanic-Orgel\"}}}}\n* {{cite web|title=F\u00f6rderverein|url=http://landesmuseum.de/website/Deutsch/Sammlungsausstellungen/Deutsches_Musikautomaten-Museum/Foerderverein.htm|accessdate=11 October 2018|ref={{sfnref|Baden State Museum: F\u00f6rderverein}}}}\n{{refend}}\n\n;S\u00fcddeutscher Barock (in German)\n{{refbegin|25em}}\n* {{cite web|last=Bieri|first=Pius|title=Residenz Bruchsal|url=http://www.sueddeutscher-barock.ch/In-Werke/a-g/Bruchsal_Residenz.html|accessdate=11 July 2018|ref={{sfnref|S\u00fcddeutscher Barock: Bruchsal}}}}\n* {{cite web|last=Bieri|first=Pius|title=Cosmas Damian Asam|url=http://www.sueddeutscher-barock.ch/In-Meister/a-g/Asam_Cosmas_Damian.html|accessdate=12 October 2019|ref={{sfnref|S\u00fcddeutscher Barock: Cosmas Damian Asam}}}}\n{{refend}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commonscat|Schloss Bruchsal}}\n* {{in lang|en}} [http://www.schloss-bruchsal.de/en/bruchsal-palace/ Official website]\n* {{in lang|de}} [https://www.tourismus-bw.de/Media/Attraktionen/Barockschloss-Bruchsal Entry on the website] of the Baden-W\u00fcrttemberg Ministry of Tourism\n* {{in lang|de}} [http://www.dmm-bruchsal.de/Musikautomaten-Museum-Sch.49.0.html Website of the ''Deutsches Musikautomaten-Museum'']\n* {{in lang|de}} [http://bruchsaler-schlosskonzerte.de/index.php/de/ Website of the Bruchsal Palace Concerts] (not used yet)\n* {{in lang|de}} [https://www.bildindex.de/ete?action=queryupdate&desc=schloss%20bruchsal%20&index=obj-all Search results for \"Schloss Bruchsal\"] on Bildindex Der Kunst & Architektur\n* {{in lang|de}} [https://www.monumente-im-bild.de/ Website with a large collection of images about Bruchsal Palace]\n\n{{Castles in Baden-W\u00fcrttemberg}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Palaces in Baden-W\u00fcrttemberg]]\n[[Category:Museums in Baden-W\u00fcrttemberg]]\n[[Category:Musical instrument museums in Germany]]\n[[Category:Music museums in Germany]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|German palace}}\n{{Infobox building\n|name=Bruchsal Palace\n|native_name=German: ''Schloss Bruchsal''\n|image=Bruchsal (23).jpg\n|caption=''[[Corps de logis]]'' from the ''[[cour d'honneur]]'', looking northwest.\n{{Collapsed infobox section begin|Map and basic information}}\n|map_type=Baden-W\u00fcrttemberg\n|map_dot_label=Bruchsal Palace\n|map_caption=Location in Baden-W\u00fcrttemberg\n|coordinates={{coord|49|7|43.33|N|8|35|55.48|E|display=inline, title}}\n|address=Schlo\u00dfraum 4, 76646<br>Bruchsal, Germany{{sfn|Bruchsal Palace: Anfahrt}}\n{{Collapsed infobox section end}}\n}}\n\n'''Bruchsal Palace''' (''Schloss Bruchsal''), also called the '''''Damiansburg''''', is a [[Baroque architecture|Baroque]] palace complex located in [[Bruchsal]], [[Germany]]. The complex is made up of over 50 buildings. These include a three-winged residential building with an attached chapel, four pavilions separated by a road, some smaller utility buildings, and a garden. It is noted for its fine Roccoco decoration and in particular its entrance staircase, which is regarded as one of the finest examples of its kind in any Baroque palace.\n\nThe palace was built in the first half of the 18th century by [[Damian Hugo Philipp von Sch\u00f6nborn]], [[Prince-Bishop of Speyer]]. Sch\u00f6nborn drew on family connections to recruit building staff and experts in the Baroque style, most notably [[Balthasar Neumann]]. Although intended to be the permanent residence of the Prince-Bishops, they occupied it for less than a century.\n\nOn 1 March 1945, only two months before the end of the [[Second World War]], much of the palace was destroyed in an American air raid directed against nearby railway installations. It has since been completely rebuilt in a restoration project that lasted until 1996. The interiors have been partly restored and the palace now houses two museums.\n\n==History==\n{{seealso|Prince-Bishopric of Speyer}}\n[[File:Udenheim-Philippsburg 1590 2.jpg|right|thumb|The Udenheim residence and castle at [[Philippsburg]], 1590]]\n\nFor much of its existence, and that of the [[Holy Roman Empire]], the city of [[Speyer]] was both an [[Imperial city]] and the seat of a [[Prince-Bishopric of Speyer|Prince-Bishopric]]. The two entities quarreled throughout their own existences, but especially during the [[Reformation]].{{sfn|S\u00fcddeutscher Barock: Bruchsal}} As in some other German Bishopric seats, this conflict would force the Prince-Bishop to vacate the city.{{sfn|Wilson|2016|p=517}} The secondary residence of the Prince-Bishops was the fortress of Udenheim,{{sfn|S\u00fcddeutscher Barock: Bruchsal}} purchased by Prince-Bishop {{ill|Emich von Leiningen|de}} in 1316.{{sfn|Baden-W\u00fcrttemberg State Archive: Findbuch 218}} Prince-Bishop [[Philipp Christoph von S\u00f6tern]] renamed that residence to the [[Philippsburg]] and began fortifying it in 1617 following the formation of the [[Protestant Union]].{{sfn|S\u00fcddeutscher Barock: Bruchsal}} In response, and with permission from the Holy Roman Emperor, [[Frederick V of the Palatinate|Frederick V, Elector Palatinate]] and a force from the Palatinate, Speyer, and [[Duchy of W\u00fcrttemberg|W\u00fcrttemberg]] destroyed Philippsburg in June 1618.{{sfn|Asbach|Schr\u00f6der|2016|p=34}}\n\nDuring the [[Nine Years' War]], French general [[Ez\u00e9chiel du Mas, Comte de M\u00e9lac]] attacked and destroyed the Philippsburg and then Speyer,{{sfn|S\u00fcddeutscher Barock: Bruchsal}}{{sfn|Mintzker|2012|pp=51\u201352}}{{sfn|Whaley|2012|p=48}} on 1 June 1689,{{sfn|Lynn|2013|p=198}} razing the city and the {{ill|Episcopal Palace (Speyer)|de|Bischofspfalz Speyer|lt=Episcopal Palace}}. Speyer's burghers were entirely unwilling to allow the reconstruction of ecclesiastical property and even violently prevented it in 1716. Prince-Bishop {{ill|Heinrich Hartard von Rollingen|de}} moved his seat to [[Bruchsal]] and rebuilt a family residence located there. Rollingen's [[coadjutor bishop]], [[Damian Hugo Philipp von Sch\u00f6nborn]], and then Prince-Bishop with the former's death in 1719, desired to rebuild the Episcopal Palace in Speyer.{{sfn|S\u00fcddeutscher Barock: Bruchsal}} Damian Hugo was refused by the city,{{sfn|Whaley|2012|p=229}}{{sfn|Gurlitt|1889|p=354}} though by then he was taken by Bruchsal's landscape and decided to build a new palace north of the town's walls. He wrote to his uncle, [[Lothar Franz von Sch\u00f6nborn]], [[Elector of Mainz]], to request the services of his court architect, [[Maximilian von Welsch]]. The request was approved, and Welsch set to work with [[Friedrich Karl von Sch\u00f6nborn]], the Prince-Bishop's brother.{{sfn|S\u00fcddeutscher Barock: Bruchsal}} Welsch presented his plans to Damian Hugo in September 1720,{{sfn|S\u00fcddeutscher Barock: Bruchsal}}{{sfn|Hempel|1965|p=158}} while he was visiting his uncle's court at {{ill|Schloss Favorite (Mainz)|de|Lustschloss Favorite (Mainz)|lt=Schloss Favorite}} to review the plans. Impressed, the Prince-Bishop approved the start of construction and in 1721 recruited Johann Georg Seitz, a [[Construction foreman|foreman]] working for another Sch\u00f6nborn.{{sfn|S\u00fcddeutscher Barock: Bruchsal}} The palace's [[cornerstone]] was laid on the north side of the ''[[cour d'honneur]]'' in what was to be the Chamber Wing (''Kammerfl\u00fcgel'') in 1722.{{sfn|Gurlitt|1889|p=354}}{{sfn|Bruchsal Palace: Stilgeschichte}}\n\n===Construction===\n[[File:Bruchsal, Schloss, N\u00f6rdliche Orangerie 20170530 004.jpg|thumb|right|The north [[orangery]], built by Johann Rohrer in 1725]]\n\nThe Chamber Wing's foundations were finished by 1723, by which time the stables and roadside pavilions were completed. After two years of work, however, Seitz departed for his original workplace, [[Wiesentheid]]. Damian Hugo fought to keep Seitz until June of that year, when he relented and hired {{ill|Johann Michael Ludwig Rohrer|de}}.{{sfn|S\u00fcddeutscher Barock: Bruchsal}} Rohrer was a master mason from [[Rastatt]],{{sfn|Hempel|1965|p=158}} employed at the court of [[Duchess Sibylle of Saxe-Lauenburg|Sibylla Augusta of Baden-Baden]], who was not only in the [[Roman Catholic Diocese of Speyer]], but also a personal friend.{{sfn|Bruchsal Palace: Damian Hugo von Sch\u00f6nborn}} Over 1724, Rohrer built the complex's [[orangeries]] and the [[Long gallery|gallery]] connecting the ''corps de logis'' to the Church Wing, itself completed in 1725. The Prince-Bishop moved into the Chamber Wing the next year and would remain there until the ''[[beletage]]'' was finished in 1730.{{sfn|S\u00fcddeutscher Barock: Bruchsal}}\n\nThe final plan for the ''corps de logis'' was only drawn up in 1725 by Rohrer and Welsch, with some input by the latter's young student, [[Anselm Franz von Ritter zu Groenesteyn]].{{sfn|S\u00fcddeutscher Barock: Bruchsal}} Over that year, Groenesteyn replaced Rohrer as the primary architect and constructed the ''corps de logis''{{'}}s first floor. Damian Hugo, however, realized that with the existing plan he would not have room for his dressing rooms nor for servants' quarters. In 1726, while Groenesteyn was absent from court,{{sfn|Bruchsal Palace: Treppenhaus}} the Prince-Bishop had a [[mezzanine floor]] constructed between the designed first and second floors. This addition made Groenesteyn's plan for the staircase impossible and, when he could not devise a new plan, he resigned.{{sfn|Hempel|1965|p=158}}{{sfn|Bruchsal Palace: Treppenhaus}} He was soon followed by Rohrer, who had fallen ill and out of Damian Hugo's favor in 1727, and [[Antonio Gresta]], charged with painting the Hofkirche's frescoes, who also grew sick in 1727 and died soon thereafter. Construction of the rest of the palace continued according to Rohrer's plans, but under the direction of an architect named Johann Georg Stahl, previously a master carpenter.{{sfn|S\u00fcddeutscher Barock: Bruchsal}}\n\nDamian Hugo complained to [[Lothar Franz von Sch\u00f6nborn]] of the situation. In Lothar Franz's employ was an architect named [[Balthasar Neumann]], who had just completed an expansion of [[Schloss Wei\u00dfenstein]]'s gardens.{{sfn|S\u00fcddeutscher Barock: Bruchsal}} Damian Hugo hired Neumann as his new master architect in 1728,{{sfn|Hempel|1965|p=158}} but he couldn't actually take charge because of the ascension of Friedrich Karl von Sch\u00f6nborn to the [[Prince-Bishopric of W\u00fcrzburg]] and his employment at the [[W\u00fcrzburg Residence]]. Meanwhile, and again acting on a recommendation from Sibylla of Baden-Baden,{{sfn|S\u00fcddeutscher Barock: Cosmas Damian Asam}} Damian Hugo hired Italian painter [[Cosmas Damian Asam]] in May 1728 to replace Gresta.{{sfn|Bruchsal Palace: Sch\u00f6nborn und der Maler}} In October of that year, Asam requested leave to go home for the winter. In the seven weeks he had been at work, Asam changed Gresta's design on the assumption that those changes had been approved by Damian Hugo. This was in error. The Prince-Bishop, assuming Asam had not managed much in the time he had been at work, has surprised to see the opposite. Though initially angry, the Prince-Bishop forgave Asam as he was impressed with the painter's ability and rewarded his labor with a hunt.{{sfn|Bruchsal Palace: Sch\u00f6nborn und der Maler}} Another painter, {{ill|Judas Thadd\u00e4us Sichelbein|de}}, was not so lucky and was dismissed on 1732.{{sfn|S\u00fcddeutscher Barock: Bruchsal}} When Neumann finally arrived at Bruchsal in March 1731,{{sfn|S\u00fcddeutscher Barock: Bruchsal}} he was tasked first and foremost with designing a new staircase. He accomplished this in 1731\u201332,{{sfn|Hempel|1965|p=158}} creating one of the world's most famous staircases.{{sfn|Pevsner|1948|pp=141, 146}} In July 1732, Damian Hugo hired {{ill|Giovanni Francesco Marchini|de}} to paint the exteriors of the other buildings of the palace complex with faux masonry. Marchini also painted the frescoes of the Entrada and the grotto behind it. From 1737 to 1743, Neumann and Stahl built the guardhouse, hunting office, arsenal, and the tower attached to the Hofkirche. The Hofkirche itself was finished in 1739.{{sfn|S\u00fcddeutscher Barock: Bruchsal}}\n\nThe ''corps de logis'' was completed in 1743, but Damian Hugo died that very same year.{{sfn|S\u00fcddeutscher Barock: Bruchsal}} He was succeeded by {{ill|Franz Christoph von Hutten zum Stolzenberg|de|lt=Franz Christoph von Hutten}},{{sfn|Bruchsal Palace: Franz Christoph von Hutten}} who found the Chamber Wing still unfinished. Neumann and Stahl, now being succeeded by his son Leonhard, continued to work at Bruchsal under Hutten.{{sfn|S\u00fcddeutscher Barock: Bruchsal}} Hutten ordered the renovation of much of the ''corps de logis'' in the [[Rococo]] style beginning in 1751 and lasting to 1754.{{sfn|Bruchsal Palace: Schloss und Garten}}{{sfn|Bruchsal Palace: Beletage}} In 1751, [[Johannes Zick]] was hired by Hutten following a recommendation from Neumann, for whom Zick had worked at W\u00fcrzburg, to paint the dome above Neumann's staircase. Another employee of Neumann's, [[Johann Michael Feuchtmayer]], was hired in 1752 to create the Rococo [[stucco]]work Hutten desired. He and Zick worked together until 1756, for example producing the Marble Hall.{{sfn|S\u00fcddeutscher Barock: Bruchsal}}\n\n[[Leopold Mozart|Leopold]], [[Maria Anna Mozart|Maria Anna]], and [[Wolfgang Amadeus Mozart]] visited Bruchsal Palace in July 1763 to begin a tour up the [[Rhine]]. Leopold wrote of the palace on 19 July, \"The Residence of Bruchsal is worth seeing, its rooms being in the very best taste, not numerous, but so noble, indescribably charming and precious.\"{{sfn|Bruchsal Palace: Franz Christoph von Hutten}}{{sfn|Heartz|2009|pp=680\u201381}}\n\n===Decline===\n[[File:Georg Maria Eckert - Schloss Bruchsal, Pagenzimmer 1870.jpg|thumb|right|alt=1870 photograph of Bruchsal Palace's interior|An 1870 photograph of the palace interior]]\n\nAs a result of the [[Coalition Wars]], the Prince-Bishopric of Speyer and the neighboring [[Margraviate of Baden]] had been forced to cede their territory on the [[left bank of the Rhine]] to France.{{sfn|Bruchsal Palace: S\u00e4kularisation}} Per the [[Treaty of Campo Formio]], Baden was to be compensated with new territory, and this was effected. Baden was given seven times the amount of land it had lost,{{sfn|Whaley|2012|pp=579, 621}} at the expense of [[Austrian Empire|Austria]] of ecclesiastical states such as the Prince-Bishopric of Speyer.{{sfn|Lefebvre|2010|p=149}} This concession was confirmed in February 1803 by the ''[[Reichsdeputationshauptschluss]]'',{{sfn|Brose|2013|p=38}} though Baden was soon raised to a [[Grand Duchy of Baden|Grand Duchy]].{{sfn|Whaley|2012|p=622}} Baden's ruler, [[Charles Frederick, Grand Duke of Baden|Charles Frederick]], summarily occupied Bruchsal and forced the departure of the last Prince-Bishop, [[Wilderich of Walderdorf|Philipp Franz von Walderdorf]]. Charles Frederick dissolved the \"Principality\" of Speyer and removed much of Bruchsal Palace's furnishings to [[Karlsruhe]], though he awarded Walderdorf a pension of 200,000 [[guilders]] and allowed him to reside at Bruchsal in the winters.{{sfn|Bruchsal Palace: S\u00e4kularisation}}{{efn|[[Wilderich of Walderdorf|Philipp Franz von Walderdorf]]'s summer residence post-secularization was the {{ill|Wagh\u00e4usel Hermitage|de|Eremitage (Wagh\u00e4usel)}}.{{sfn|Bruchsal Palace: S\u00e4kularisation}}}}\n\nWhen Charles Frederick died in 1806, Walderdorf shared Bruchsal with the Grand Duke's widow, [[Amalie of Hesse-Darmstadt]] with her unmarried daughter, {{ill|Amalie Christiane von Baden|de}}, who had been replaced at court by [[St\u00e9phanie de Beauharnais]].{{sfn|Bruchsal Palace: F\u00fcrstliche Langeweile}} Amalie spent three to four months of every summer at the palace,{{sfn|Hirsch|1906|p=2}} time she spent in a constant monotony that she often took vacations to escape.{{sfn|Bruchsal Palace: F\u00fcrstliche Langeweile}} Amalie's household at Bruchsal and its upkeep was at her own expense.{{sfn|Hirsch|1906|p=3}} The early 19th century traveler Charles Edward Dodd, who visited the palace around 1818, described its \"deserted splendour\" wherein \"the gay ladies of [Princess Amalie's] court complain bitterly of its magnificent dreariness.\"{{sfn|Dodd|1818|pp=163\u201364}} Two other contemporary visitors, [[Frederick William III of Prussia]] and [[Elizabeth of Russia]], also noted the droll state of Bruchsal Palace.{{sfn|Bruchsal Palace: F\u00fcrstliche Langeweile}} Bruchsal's citizenry adored Amalie, though, and mourned her death on 27 July 1832.{{sfn|Hirsch|1906|pp=7\u20138}}\n\nFollowing Amalie von Baden's death, Bruchsal Palace was used for myriad purposes while it steadily deteriorated.{{sfn|Bruchsal Palace: Verlassene Schloss}} In 1849, during the [[Baden Revolution]], the ground floor of the ''corps de logis'' was used for a [[barrack]] and later a [[military hospital]] for Prussian soldiers.{{Sfn|Hirsch|1906|pp=16\u201317}}\n\nIn 1869, two years before the palace vanished from guide books in Germany, the Grand Duchy of Baden's Ministry of the Interior made plans to move a Catholic seminary into the palace. A major renovation was planned to fit the school, but were short lived. A decade later in 1880, the court jeweler of the Landgrave of Hesse wrote to the Badener government on behalf of the Vicomte de Montfort, a Parisian aristocrat. The Vicomte desired to reside at the palace and renovate it, but his request was rejected.{{sfn|Bruchsal Palace: Verlassene Schloss}} Beginning at this time, hundreds of high-quality photographs were made of the palace's interiors.{{sfn|Bruchsal Palace: Zerst\u00f6rung und Wiederaufbau}}\n\nA restoration of the palace grounds was carried out at Bruchsal from 1900 to 1909 under the direction of German art historian Fritz Hirsch.{{Sfn|S\u00fcddeutscher Barock: Bruchsal}}\n\nThe [[Grand Duchy of Baden]] was dissolved on 9 November 1918 and was followed by Grand Duke [[Frederick II, Grand Duke of Baden|Frederick II]]'s abdication on 22 November.{{sfn|Bruchsal Palace: Das Ende der Monarchie}}\n\nThe ''beletage'' was opened to the public as a permanent exhibit of the palace's treasures in the 1920s.{{sfn|Bruchsal Palace: Das Ende der Monarchie}}\n\n===Destruction and restoration===\n[[File:Schloss Bruchsal Corps de Logis 1945.jpg|thumb|right|Ruins of Bruchsal Palace in 1945]]\n\nIn the closing days of the [[Second World War]], the [[American Army Air Force]] bombed [[Bruchsal]] to disable its railway facilities. In one raid on 1 March 1945, the [[379th Expeditionary Operations Group]] attacked and destroyed the city's [[marshaling yard]].{{sfn|Banks|2000|p=338}} 80% of the city was destroyed, as was Bruchsal Palace, incinerated to just the staircase and some of the facade. Reconstruction, aided by the pictures taken in the late 19th century, began the next year with some of the minor buildings put back together to provide administrative offices and temporary housing.{{sfn|Bruchsal Palace: Zerst\u00f6rung und Wiederaufbau}} In 1947, work on the residential structure began in the Chamber Wing. The shell of the ''corps de logis'' was rebuilt from 1953 to 1956, though conversely the church wing was demolished in 1959.{{sfn|S\u00fcddeutscher Barock: Bruchsal}}\n\nThe palace was reopened on 28 February 1975,{{sfn|City of Bruchsal: Schloss Bruchsal}} though reconstruction on the facades lasted two more years.{{sfn|S\u00fcddeutscher Barock: Bruchsal}} The reconstitution of the palace's many frescoes continued until 1996.{{sfn|Bruchsal Palace: Zerst\u00f6rung und Wiederaufbau}}\n\nTo commemorate the 50th anniversary of the [[France\u2013Germany relations#Friendship|Franco-German friendship]], French President [[Fran\u00e7ois Mitterrand]] and German Chancellor [[Helmut Kohl]] met at Bruchsal Palace on 12 November 1987.{{sfn|Bruchsal Palace: Mitterand und Kohl}}\n\nThe 12th DiGA Garden Festival was held here from 25 to 27 May 2018.{{sfn|City of Bruchsal: DiGA - Die Gartenmesse}}\n\n==Architecture==\n[[File:Bruchsal, Schloss, Corps de Logis, Kammerfl\u00fcgel, von S\u00fcdosten 20170530 001.jpg|thumb|right|The ''corps de logis'' and the Chamber Wing]]\n\nSometimes called the Damiansburg (''Damian's Castle''), after [[Damian Hugo Philipp von Sch\u00f6nborn|Damian Hugo von Sch\u00f6nborn]], who built the palace with unconventional methods and purpose. Damian Hugo built the palace with careful financing and a reliance on local industry, which allowed him to maintain a positive annual income despite the cost of construction. Additionally, the palace was built of [[brick]] in response to the French destruction by fire of the {{ill|Episcopal Palace (Speyer)|de|Bischofspfalz Speyer|lt=Episcopal Palace in Speyer}}.{{sfn|Kaufmann|1995|p=319}}\n\nThe exteriors of several of the palace complex's brick buildings are painted to appear to be made of masonry.{{sfn|Bruchsal Palace: Stilgeschichte}} The facades of the two wings off the ''corps de logis'' are defined by ''[[risalit]]e'', made up of a [[balcony]] atop a door, and are discriminated by [[pilasters]] that also form the buildings' corners.{{sfn|Gurlitt|1889|p=354}}\n\nDespite Damian Hugo's love of the Viennese Baroque aesthetic and the work of [[Balthasar Neumann]], Bruchsal Palace bears Westphalian and Dutch influence, thanks to [[Johann Conrad Schlaun]].{{sfn|Kaufmann|1995|p=319}} Damian Hugo began with a French-style plan in 1720, but changed his plans after [[Papal conclave, 1721|the next year's Papal Conclave]] and incorporated Italian, Dutch, and English influences in addition.{{sfn|Whaley|2012|p=229}} The interiors of Bruchsal Palace share many similarities with the W\u00fcrzburg Residence. The stucco ornamentation within, mostly of the Rococo style, is French-influenced.{{sfn|Gurlitt|1889|p=356}}\n\nTo save money, Damian Hugo used the same architects as at other Sch\u00f6nborn family projects.{{sfn|Bruchsal Palace: Damian Hugo von Sch\u00f6nborn}} One of these was [[Balthasar Neumann]], author of the [[W\u00fcrzburg Residence]], the palace of Damian Hugo's brothers. Neumann worked at Bruchsal as chief architect from 1731 until his death in 1753.{{sfn|Bruchsal Palace: Architekt Balthasar Neumann}} The frugal Damian Hugo was succeeded by Hutten, who brought pomp and chic to Bruchsal.{{sfn|Bruchsal Palace: Franz Christoph von Hutten}} He renovated the second floor in the [[Rococo]] style from 1751 to 1754.{{sfn|Bruchsal Palace: Stilgeschichte}}{{sfn|Bruchsal Palace: Beletage}} When [[Leopold Mozart]] visited in 1763, he described Bruchsal as being of \"the very best taste\".{{sfn|Bruchsal Palace: Franz Christoph von Hutten}}\n\nDamian Hugo personally knew virtually none of the artisans that worked at Bruchsal Palace and relied on recommendations from family and friends like [[Duchess Sibylle of Saxe-Lauenburg|Sibylla Augusta of Baden-Baden]], the Margravine of Baden. Johann Rohrer, Cosmas Damian Asam, and [[Egid Quirin Asam]] were among the men recommended to Damian Hugo by the Margravine.{{sfn|S\u00fcddeutscher Barock: Bruchsal}}\n\nFrom 1725 to his dismissal in 1727, Rohrer prepared 717 plans for Bruchsal Palace, 63 of which were for the Hofkirche alone.{{sfn|S\u00fcddeutscher Barock: Bruchsal}}\n\nNeumann worked at Bruchsal on and off with Johann Georg Stahl from 1731 to his death in 1753.{{sfn|S\u00fcddeutscher Barock: Bruchsal}}\n\nThe chamber music hall, decorated in the [[Louis XVI style]], represents an experiment in early [[Neoclassical architecture|Neoclassicism]].{{sfn|Bruchsal Palace: Stilgeschichte}}\n\nRenovations in the 1970s revealed the original Baroque frescoes of the \"leaf room\" (''Laubenzimmer''). They are thought to have been painted by Marchini, as they resemble his work from Damian Hugo at [[Schloss Favorite (Rastatt)|Schloss Favorite in Rastatt]] in 1718. The design itself, wooden lattices interlaced with vines and birds, is an Italianate design that originated in the 16th and 17th centuries.{{sfn|Bruchsal Palace: Laubenzimmer}}\n\nThe German art historian [[Cornelius Gurlitt (art historian)|Cornelius Gurlitt]] extensively praised the artifice of Bruchsal Palace in his 1889 work ''History of the Baroque and Rococo Styles in Germany''.{{sfn|Gurlitt|1889|p=356}}\n\n===Ground floor===\nForming the entrance to the palace is an entrance hall called the Intrada, containing a ceiling [[fresco]] of personifications of the [[seven virtues]] defeating the [[Seven deadly sins|seven sins]] by {{ill|Giovanni Francesco Marchini|de}}, who was responsible for most of the paintings on the ground floor. Above the pillars are windowed galleries into the servant quarters, which were not in the plans of the palace and were forced by [[Damian Hugo Philipp von Sch\u00f6nborn]] in 1726 and forced a redesign of the staircase.{{sfn|Bruchsal Palace: Erdgeschoss}}\n\nEnclosed by [[Balthasar Neumann]]'s grand staircase is the Grotto, dimly lit in imitation of a cave and decorated by Marchini with murals of plantlife, shells, and river deities beneath a ceiling fresco of a bird-filled sky. Marchini's work in the Grotto, although still reddened by fire, was restored after [[World War II]] but not in the neighboring Garden Hall, which survived the war but suffered water and frost damage. The ceiling fresco remains unrestored in a permanent exhibition of the palace's destruction in 1945.{{sfn|Bruchsal Palace: Erdgeschoss}}\n\n===Staircase===\n[[File:BruchsalSchlossTreppe1.jpg|thumb|right|alt=Photo of Bruchsal Palace's staircase|The base of the two arms of the palace staircase.]]\n\nEntered from the back of the Intrada and wrapping around the Grotto is the Staircase, built by [[Balthasar Neumann]] from 1731 to 1732.{{sfn|Hempel|1965|p=158}} [[Anselm Franz von Ritter zu Groenesteyn]]'s 1725 plan for the palace was ordinary,{{sfn|Bruchsal Palace: Treppenhaus}} perhaps inspired by the [[Palazzo Carignano]],{{sfn|Templer|1995|p=150}} but Prince-Bishop Damian Hugo added a [[mezzanine]] between the first and second floors to make room for his dressing rooms and quarters for his servant staff. In doing so, the designed staircase was now too short to reach the second floor and Groenesteyn could not amend the issue. In 1731, Balthasar Neumann set to work to fill the gap,{{sfn|Bruchsal Palace: Treppenhaus}} drawing up a design for a [[spiral staircase]] \u2013 a feature that had not been common in German architecture since the [[Middle Ages]].{{sfn|Kaufmann|1995|pp=387-388}} Neumann also extended the upper landing to connect the ''[[beletage]]''{{'}}s two state rooms and thereby formed an oval that was then wrapped with a pair of staircases. This staircase has, since its construction, been the object of much praise.{{sfn|Gurlitt|1889|p=354}}{{sfn|Hempel|1965|pp=158\u201359}}{{sfn|Templer|1995|pp=127, 150}}{{sfn|Eberle|2008|p=3}} Noted historian of art and architecture [[Nikolaus Pevsner]] held Bruchsal Palace, and especially its staircase, in high regard. Of the latter, he wrote in ''An Outline of European Architecture'':{{sfn|Pevsner|1948|pp=141, 146}}\n\n{{quote|text=But the staircase at Bruchsal is unique. Words can hardly re-evoke the enchanting sensation that one experiences in walking up one of its two arms. [...] Bruchsal with its perfect unity of space and decorations was the high-water mark of the Baroque style.}}\n\n===Second floor===\n[[File:09 Bruchsal (29).JPG|thumb|right|alt=|A corner of Prince's Hall, reminiscent of the [[H\u00f4tel de Soubise]]]]\n\nAbove the staircase is a massive fresco, covering the entire dome, painted by [[Johannes Zick]] in 1752. Zick's fresco documents and glorifies the construction projects of Prince-Bishops Damian Hugo von Sch\u00f6nborn and Franz Christoph von Hutten. Male figures in the fresco represent architecture and construction, while female figures represent painting and sculpture. To the left of von Hutten are thought to be the two foremen of the palace's construction, Johann Georg Stahl and his son, Johann Leonhard.{{sfn|Bruchsal Palace: Deckenfresko}}\n\nThe entrance to the second floor is a large chamber and dome at the top of the stairs{{sfn|Gurlitt|1889|p=354}} decorated by artists who had previously worked at the [[W\u00fcrzburg Residence]]. Woodcarver {{ill|Ferdinand Hundt|de}} created the paneling, [[Johann Michael Feuchtmayer]] produced the stucco, and [[Johannes Zick]] painted the [[fresco]]es. Zick's ceiling fresco depicts the history of the [[Bishopric of Speyer|Bishops of Speyer]], beginning with Jesse in the 4th century and ending with Damian Hugo and Hutten, who are portrayed as patrons of the arts and architecture.{{sfn|Bruchsal Palace: Fest\u00e4le}}\n\nThe Prince's Hall ({{lang-de|F\u00fcrstensaal}}) is one of two [[ballroom]]s on the ''[[beletage]]''; it is the southern of the two. The hall also functions as an [[ahnentafel]], bearing portraits of the Prince-Bishops from {{ill|Eberhard von Dienheim|de}} to [[Wilderich of Walderdorf]], the final Prince-Bishop. The other hall, to the north, is the Marble Hall. It features a massive ceiling fresco painted by Johannes Zick and his son [[Januarius Zick|Januarius]].{{sfn|Bruchsal Palace: Fest\u00e4le}} The stucco and fireplace and mirrors of the Prince's Hall are French in nature, resembling the interior of the [[H\u00f4tel de Soubise]], but also Austria's [[St. Florian Monastery]].{{sfn|Gurlitt|1889|p=356}}\n\nThe apartments on the south side of the main building were remodeled by Johann Michael Feuchtmayer for Hutten in the 1760s. Walderdorff lived in them from his abdication as Prince-Bishop in 1802 until his death.{{Sfn|Bruchsal Palace: Beletage}} The southern state apartment opens with an [[antechamber]] containing some surviving examples of original Rococo stucco, furniture by [[Abraham Roentgen]], and some of the oldest tapestries in the palace's collection. Next is the Prince-Bishop's audience chamber, also housing original furnishings removed from the palace in 1939. Among these items is a life-size portrait of Hutten painted by Johann Nikolaus Treu. Past the [[bedroom]] are the Watteau Cabinet, used as a [[wardrobe]] and destroyed during WWII, and the room of the Prince-Bishop's [[Chamberlain (office)|chamberlain]].{{sfn|Bruchsal Palace: S\u00fcdliche Staatsappartement}}\n\nThe private apartments of the last Prince-Bishop are comparatively modest compared to the other ''beletage'' [[Enfilade (architecture)|enfilades]]. The most private rooms were marked by [[still life]], [[Landscape painting|landscape]], or [[Genre painting|genre]] overdoor paintings, such as the still life overdoors in the dining hall. On display in the gallery room are a number of paintings and furnishings owned by the Prince-Bishop until their relocation in the 19th century. The last of this suite's rooms is the Blue Room, decorated in 1810 with blue silks for [[Frederica of Baden]]. The room houses two tapestries from [[Ovid]]'s ''[[Metamorphoses]]'', depicting [[Leda (mythology)|Leda]] and [[Europa (consort of Zeus)|Europa]].{{Sfn|Bruchsal Palace: F\u00fcrstbisch\u00f6fliche Privatr\u00e4ume}}\n\nThe northern state apartment also starts with an antechamber attached to the Marble Hall, adorned with stucco reliefs of hunting and fishing. This room also houses the ''Groteskenfolge'',{{sfn|Bruchsal Palace: N\u00f6rdliche Staatsappartement}} a six-part tapestry series made from 1685 to 1717 by the Philippe Behagle manufactury in [[Beauvais]].{{sfn|Bruchsal Palace: Tapisserien}} The succeeding room is similarly ornamented, but with musical instruments and an [[overdoor]] painting depicting the tale of [[Gaius Mucius Scaevola]]. The largest room in the suite is the [[throne room]], decorated with more tapestries. In between the throne room and suite's bedroom is a chapel.{{sfn|Bruchsal Palace: N\u00f6rdliche Staatsappartement}}\n\nAmalie von Baden had her apartment renovated in 1806 in the [[Empire style]]. Her antechamber contains four tapestries of [[exoticism|exotic]] settings made by the [[Aubusson tapestry|Aubusson manufactory]]. Adjoining this is Amalie's audience room, containing more paintings from the original palace collection, and French-made furniture. Next is the Yellow Room, a [[living room]] containing more tapestries, made in [[Brussels]] between 1550 and 1575. The last room in Amalie's apartment is her bedroom, which furnished from 1810 to 1815 in high Empire style fashion.{{sfn|Bruchsal Palace: Appartement der Amalie von Baden}}\n\n===Hofkirche===\n[[File:ETH-BIB-Bruchsal, Schlosskirche, Int\u00e9rieur-Dia 247-05275.tif|thumb|right|The Hofkirche in 1930]]\n\nThe Hofkirche is connected to the palace's left wing by a narrow hall. It was designed by Balthasar Neumann in 1740 and painted painted by [[Cosmas Damian Asam]].{{sfn|Bruchsal Palace: Hofkirche}} Asam was appointed in 1728 following the sudden death of the painter previously contracted to create the fresco, [[Antonio Gresta]]. Despite some animosity from Damian Hugo toward him,{{sfn|Bruchsal Palace: Sch\u00f6nborn und der Maler}} Asam painted the ceiling with images of [[Saints Cosmas and Damian|Saints Cosmas, Damian]], and [[Hugh of Ch\u00e2teauneuf|Hugh]] in light pastels, impressing the Prince-Bishop. The Hofkirche was destroyed in World War II and a new church was built in its place from 1960 to 1966, with work by [[Fritz Wotruba]] and [[HAP Grieshaber]].{{sfn|Bruchsal Palace: Hofkirche}}\n\nNine bronze statuettes of the [[Twelve Apostles]], made in [[Augsburg]] around 1593, were recovered from the post-1945 wreckage of the Hofkirche and are today on display in the modern chapel.{{sfn|Bruchsal Palace: Hofkirche}}\n\n===North wing===\nThe [[chamber music]] hall, ''Kammermusiksaal'', was designed and decorated by {{ill|Joachim G\u00fcnther (sculptor)|de|Joachim G\u00fcnther (Bildhauer)|lt=Joachim G\u00fcnther}} for [[August Philip of Limburg Stirum]] in 1776. The room was originally two stories high, but a fake roof was put in place during G\u00fcnther's renovation. Its yellow walls are covered in vibrant early [[Neoclassicism|Neoclassical]] stucco of floral friezes and [[garland]]s of wind instruments. The Kammermusiksaal was the significant first room in the palace to be fully restored, being completed in 1955.{{sfn|Bruchsal Palace: Kammermusiksaal}}\n\n==Grounds and gardens==\n[[File:Plan-Schloss-Bruchsal.png|thumb|right|Plan of Bruchsal Palace's grounds. The Ehrenhof is at the center of the map.{{sfn|Hirsch|1906|p=x}}]]\n\nIn totality, there were 50 buildings on the grounds of Bruchsal Palace.{{sfn|Bruchsal Palace: Geb\u00e4ude}} The main palace area takes up {{convert|5400|m2|sp=us}}.<ref>{{cite web|title=Ehrenhof|url=https://www.schloss-bruchsal.de/fileadmin/Raum/Pdf/13_bruchsal/ssg_schloss-bruchsal_vermietung_ehrenhof.pdf|publisher=Staatliche Schl\u00f6sser und G\u00e4rten Baden-W\u00fcrttemberg|language=de|accessdate=9 March 2019}}</ref> It is located at the center of the palace grounds.{{sfn|Bruchsal Palace: Geb\u00e4ude}} Attached to the main building are two wings for the palace chapel and the apartments of the Prince-Bishop's courtiers.{{sfn|Gurlitt|1889|p=354}}\n\nWelsch's original plan for the complex, discovered in 2010 at the [[Austrian National Library]] in [[Vienna]], where Friedrich Karl was based, was of a three-wing composition similar to a 1711 plan of [[Schloss Wei\u00dfenstein]] by [[Johann Dientzenhofer]]. The original plan, with the exception of the ''corps de logis'' survived into the existing structure. It placed the palace complex on a right-angle to the road leading from Bruchsal's north-east gate, {{convert|1000|ft|m|sp=us}} distant. That road, now called the Sch\u00f6nbornstrasse, would have separated two sets of four identical buildings.{{sfn|S\u00fcddeutscher Barock: Bruchsal}}\n\nThe palace gardens (Schlossgarten) lie along a north-west running [[Avenue (landscape)|avenue]] called the Schlossraum.<ref>{{cite web|title=Schlossgarten|url=https://www.google.com/maps/place/Schlossgarten,+76646+Bruchsal,+Germany/@49.1292316,8.5955512,283m/data=!3m1!1e3!4m12!1m6!3m5!1s0x4797a3e067db7ad3:0x5141090414e888bb!2sCastle+of+Bruchsal!8m2!3d49.12892!4d8.598326!3m4!1s0x4797a3e10d5417e7:0x1f657d98da624e11!8m2!3d49.1298561!4d8.5948927|publisher=[[Google Maps]]|accessdate=17 September 2018}}</ref> The Schlossraum is lined with statuary produced in the 1750s by the workshop of Joachim G\u00fcnther depicting the classical elements and the four seasons, while an additional four \"guardians\" stand in the lower garden, near the pools.{{sfn|Bruchsal Palace: Der Garten}} The garden itself was first laid out in 1723 and was then doubled in size in 1728. This was replaced in 1770 with an [[English landscape garden]]. A railroad track constructed in 1843 shortened the length from {{convert|800|m|ft|sp=us}} to just {{convert|300|m|ft|sp=us}}.{{sfn|S\u00fcddeutscher Barock: Bruchsal}}\n\nIn front of the chancellery (now the district courthouse) is the Amalienbrunnen, erected in 1911 and dedicated to Amalie von Baden.{{sfn|Bruchsal Palace: F\u00fcrstliche Langeweile}} It stands in front of the {{ill|Amtsgericht Bruchsal|de}}.\n\nThe grounds of Bruchsal Palace are occasionally used to host festivities such as an annual [[Christmas market]] (''Weihnachtsmarkt'') and festival, established in 2009.{{sfn|Schlossweihnachtsmarkt Bruchsal}}\n\n===Museums===\nThe two main museums at Bruchsal Palace are the ''Deutsches Musikautomaten-Museum'' (German music machine museum), maintained by the {{ill|Baden State Museum|de|Badisches Landesmuseum}}, and the Municipal History Museum. The ''Deutsches Musikautomaten-Museum'', founded in 1984,{{sfn|Baden State Museum: F\u00f6rderverein}} exhibits some 500 examples of German-made \"automatic musical machines,\"{{sfn|Bruchsal Palace: Ausstellungen}} such as a self-playing replica of the [[Titanic|RMS ''Titanic'']]'s organ,{{sfn|Baden State Museum: Die \"Titanic-Orgel\"}} from the 17th to the 21st centuries on three floors of the palace. They are all displayed in a setting contemporary to their production, highlighting their place in society.{{sfn|Baden State Museum: Deutsches Musikautomaten-Museum}} Audio recordings of the collection's various pieces is available on the Baden State Museum's website.{{sfn|Baden State Museum: Musikautomaten-Galerie}} The Municipal Museum, on the third floor of the palace, traces the history of [[Bruchsal]] from the Neolithic to the modern day. Focal points are the history of the penal system in the city and Bruchsal's destruction in the [[Second World War]].{{sfn|City of Bruchsal: St\u00e4dtisches Museum}}\n\n''Built, Destroyed, Resurrected'' (''Gebaut, Zerst\u00f6rt, Wiedererstanden'') is a permanent exhibit documenting the destruction of Bruchsal Palace on 1 March 1945. It displays pieces of the pre-war palace and the [[black-and-white photograph]]s used to reconstruct its interiors.{{sfn|Bruchsal Palace: Ausstellungen}}\n\nThe [[lapidary]], in the basement of a southern connecting building, contains stone sculptures from the residential building and surrounding structures. Examples include coats of arms, [[putti]]s and [[Dwarf (mythology)|dwarves]], [[Capital (architecture)|capitals]], and [[balustrade]] pieces.{{sfn|Bruchsal Palace: Ausstellungen}}\n\n{{Panorama|image=File:BruchsalSchlossHofPano2.jpg|height=230px|caption=Bruchsal Palace from the ''[[cour d'honneur]]''.}}\n\n==Notes==\n{{reflist|group=lower-alpha}}\n\n===Citations===\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==References==\n{{refbegin}}\n* {{cite book|last1=Asbach|first1=Olaf|last2=