he series because having only three fingers and a thumb on each hand (as Pat does) was a [[Yakuza]] symbol.<ref>[http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/entertainment/720419.stm Bob the Builder fixed for Japan], BBC News.</ref> The series is dubbed into Japanese.\n*In the United States, newer episodes of Postman Pat initially aired weekdays at 8:00 AM Eastern time on the [[HBO Family]] cable network. The 2004 series used to broadcast weekends on the [[Qubo]] channel; the episodes were unaltered. Postman Pat no longer airs in the United States.\n*In Iran, Postman Pat was broadcast in the late 1980s and early 1990s. The show was dubbed into Persian under the name ''Pat-e Postchi''.<ref>[http://www.blockbuster.com/catalog/movieDetails/306511 Blockbuster Online \u2013 Postman Pat] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100619163229/http://www.blockbuster.com/catalog/movieDetails/306511 |date=19 June 2010 }}</ref>\n*In Israel, Postman Pat first aired as ''Dar haDavar'' (\u05d3\u05e8 \u05d4\u05d3\u05d5\u05d5\u05e8) on the [[Israeli Educational Television]] in 1994, then as ''Dani haDavar'' (\u05d3\u05e0\u05d9 \u05d4\u05d3\u05d5\u05d5\u05e8) on the [[Hop! Channel]] in the early 2000s and then on the IETV again as ''Dan haDavar'' (\u05d3\u05df \u05d4\u05d3\u05d5\u05d5\u05e8). All three versions were dubbed into Hebrew.\n*In the Philippines, the series aired on [[TV5 (Philippines)|TV5]], dubbed into [[Tagalog language|Tagalog]]. [[Cartoon Network (Philippines)]] also broadcasts until 2008 or 2009. The series was broadcast on the defunct Filipino television network [[Studio 23]].\n* In Canada, Postman Pat is shown on the [[Treehouse TV|Treehouse Children's Network]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://treehousetv.com/watch/shows/postman_pat/default.aspx|title=Postman Pat at Treehouse TV|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120630011934/http://treehousetv.com/watch/shows/postman_pat/default.aspx|archivedate=30 June 2012|df=dmy-all}}</ref> The original series also aired on cable and satellite television on its youth and children's network [[YTV (TV channel)|YTV]] and on digital television on the BBC's channel for children [[BBC Kids]].\n*In South Africa, Postman Pat was broadcast on [[M-Net]] being shown on their children's block ''[[K-T.V.]]''. It was later moved to [[SABC 2]] and later returned to air on [[M-Net]] with its 2003 series and ''Special Delivery Service''.\n*In Malaysia, Postman Pat aired on [[TV3 (Malaysia)|TV3]] and was shown on Friday afternoons at 5:32pm with the series being reedited into two episodes.\n*In Thailand, Postman Pat was played on [[UBC Movies and Kids]] and was also reedited into two episodes.\n*In Namibia, Postman Pat was shown on [[South West African Broadcasting Corporation|SWABC]] during the mid 1980s. In 1992 the [[M-Net]] network was launched and broadcast for the first time in Namibia which included the series' airings, broadcasts and reruns on [[M-Net]] as well as being part of ''[[K-T.V.]]'' for Namibian viewers. The next few years [[M-Net]] (along with the series' airings on the channel) was launched and broadcast in several African countries including Botswana and Ghana in 1993, Nigeria in 1994, Kenya and Zambia in 1995 and Tanzania in 1997. Franchises to the channel were launched in other African countries including Zimbabwe in 1995, Malawi in 1997, Angola in 1998 and Mozambique and Ethiopia in 2000.\n*In Singapore, Postman Pat was broadcast on [[MediaCorp Central|Premiere 12]]. It started airing in Singapore for the first time on 8 August 1997. Later in the 2000s and 2010s, the 2003 series and ''Special Delivery Service'' both aired on [[Central (TV channel)|Central]] and [[Okto]] as part of their lineup of children's programmes.\n*In the Middle East and Saudi Arabia, Postman Pat was broadcast on the Arabic children's television station [[MBC 3]] and on cable television on [[Nickelodeon Arabia|Nickelodeon]] for [[Showtime Arabia]] and the former children's cable television network [[Fun Channel]] for [[OSN|Orbit]].\n*In Kuwait, Postman Pat was played on the country's English network [[KTV2]].\n*In Jordan, Postman Pat was shown on the English television network [[Jordan Radio and Television Corporation|Channel 2]].\n*In Ghana, Postman Pat was broadcast on [[TV3 Ghana|TV3]].\n*In Brunei, the original Postman Pat series and specials were aired on [[Radio Television Brunei|RTB]].\n\n===Europe===\n*In Scotland, Postman Pat is shown not only in English but also sometimes broadcast as ''P\u00e0draig Post'', in the [[Scottish Gaelic language|Gaelic language]], on [[BBC Scotland]].\n\n*In Ireland, Postman Pat was broadcast on [[RT\u00c92]] and aired on their biggest children's block ''[[The Den (Ireland)|The Den]]'' From 14 September 1989 onwards.\nViewers can also receive BBC broadcasts in much of the country via cable and satellite services as well as terrestrial overspill. \n*In the Netherlands the series was also shown dubbed in [[Dutch language|Dutch]]. There the series is called ''Pieter Post''. It was first broadcast by [[NCRV]], later on [[Kindernet|Nick Kindernet]] and [[Nickelodeon]].\n*In [[Galicia (Spain)|Galicia]] (Spain), Postman Pat is broadcast as ''O Carteiro Pat'', in [[Galician language]], on [[TVG (Galicia)|Televisi\u00f3n de Galicia]].\n*In [[Catalonia]] (Spain), Postman Pat is broadcast as ''Pat el carter'', in [[Catalan language]], on [[TV3 (Catalonia)|Televisi\u00f3 de Catalunya]]. In fact, the original 1981 series was one of the first animation series shown on the channel, in 1984.\n*In Italy ''Il postino Pat'' has aired at various times on the [[RAI|RaiSat Ragazzi]] channel, [[Raitre]] and RaiSat YOYO.\n*In Poland the adventures of ''Listonosz Pat'' is shown on [[MiniMini]] and [[TVP1]].\n*In Spain Postman Pat is known as ''Pat el cartero'' and is shown dubbed in Spanish on [[Clan TVE]].\n*In Iceland, ''P\u00f3sturinn P\u00e1ll'' is how Pat is known to the viewers of [[R\u00daV (television channel)|Sj\u00f3nvarpi\u00f0]], the public Icelandic television network.\n*In Austria and Germany, Postman Pat has been broadcast on [[ORF (broadcaster)|ORF]] (Austria) and [[Super RTL]] (Germany) with the name \"Postbote Pat\".\n*In France, Postman Pat is called \"Pierre Martin\" and was played on [[France 3]], [[Nickelodeon Junior]], [[Piwi+]], and [[TFO|Mini TFO]], dubbed French.\n*In Portugal, Postman Pat is known as \"O Carteiro Paulo\" and is shown on [[RTP2]], [[MOV (TV channel)|MOV]] and [[Canal Panda]], dubbed into Portuguese.\n*In Sweden, Postman Pat is known as ''Postis-Per'' and is shown on [[TV4 (Sweden)|TV4]], dubbed into Swedish.\n*In Denmark, Postman Pat is known as ''Postmand Per'' and is shown on [[DR (broadcaster)|DR]], dubbed into Danish.\n*In Norway, Postman Pat is known as ''Postmann Pat'' and is shown on [[NRK]], first narrated in [[Norwegian language|Norwegian]] by [[Sverre Anker Ousdal]] in the first seasons, then dubbed into Norwegian in the modern seasons.\n*In Finland, Postman Pat is known as ''Postimies Pate'' and is shown on [[Yleisradio|YLE]], dubbed into Finnish.\n*In Greece, Postman Pat was also known as \"Taxydromos Pat\" (\u03a4\u03b1\u03c7\u03c5\u03b4\u03c1\u03cc\u03bc\u03bf\u03c2 \u03a0\u03b1\u03c4 - Tahhydromos Pat) and was shown on [[Alter Channel|ALTER]] until the station's closure. From November 2016 to January 2017, it was shown on [[ERT2]].\n*In United Arab Emirates, ''Postman Pat'' was shown on [[e-Junior]].\n\n==Postman Pat Village at Longleat==\n[[Longleat Safari Park]] had an outdoor reproduction of Greendale village, including the Post Office, the Clifton's house and the Greendale station. It also had a miniature model of Greendale.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.longleat.co.uk/attractions/postman-pats-village.html|title=Longleat \u2013 As featured on BBC's Animal Park<!-- Bot generated title -->|publisher=}}</ref> It was installed during the 1990s, was relocated during 2008 in preparation for a new animal area and was revamped a third time for 2013. The attraction was closed at the end of 2015 and was permanently removed in 2016.\n\n==Award nominations==\nIn 2006, Postman Pat was nominated for \"Best Pre-school Animation Series\" at the [[BAFTA Children's Awards]].<ref name=\"bafta-2006\">{{cite web|url=http://www.bafta.org/awards/childrens/nominations/?year=2006|title=Past Winners and Nominees \u2013 Children's \u2013 Awards \u2013 2006|publisher=[[BAFTA]]|accessdate=17 March 2010}}</ref>\n\n==Parodies==\n* ''[[Harry Enfield and Chums]]'' featured a parody entitled \"Il Postino Pat\" (the show's Italian title), with an operatic reworking of the theme tune and the characters speaking in Italian. At the end there is a [[communist]] revolution in Greendale and Pat is shot and killed by fascist soldiers.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=vQDZ1uFZBkU|title=YouTube|website=www.youtube.com}}</ref>\n* ''[[Harry and Paul]]'' parodied Postman Pat in series 3 and 4 with \"Parking Pataweyo\", an African immigrant working as a stereotypically uncompromising traffic warden, played by [[Daniel Kaluuya]], whose name and theme tune are based on Pat's.\n* ''[[Spitting Image]]'' in 1987 the topical satirical puppet series, featured Temporary Postman Pratt<ref>[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=JxQD1MNbdeg \"Temporary Postman Pratt on Spitting Image (ITV)\"], ''Spitting Image (ITV)''.</ref> in a send-up of Royal Mail's employment of temporary postal workers during busy times. In the opening titles, Pratt can be seen driving a familiar (though yellow in colour) van along country roads before running over a black and white cat.  Pratt likes to clear his workload as quickly as he can by dumping the post rather than delivering it. He is portrayed as a student who is lazy and rude.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commonscat}}\n* {{IMDb title|id=0149509|title=Postman Pat}}\n* {{tv.com show|postman-pat}}\n* {{Screenonline TV title|562690}}\n\n{{Postman Pat}}\n\n[[Category:British children's animated television programmes]]\n[[Category:1980s British animated television series]]\n[[Category:1980s British children's television series]]\n[[Category:1981 British television series debuts]]\n[[Category:1990s British animated television series]]\n[[Category:1990s British children's television series]]\n[[Category:2000s British animated television series]]\n[[Category:2000s British children's television series]]\n[[Category:2010s British animated television series]]\n[[Category:2010s British children's television series]]\n[[Category:2017 British television series endings]]\n[[Category:BBC children's television programmes]]\n[[Category:British stop-motion animated television series]]\n[[Category:DreamWorks Classics]]\n[[Category:DreamWorks Classics franchises]]\n[[Category:English-language television programs]]\n[[Category:Fictional postal workers]]\n[[Category:Media franchises]]\n[[Category:Television programs adapted into films]]\n[[Category:Television programs adapted into novels]]\n[[Category:Television series by DreamWorks Animation]]\n[[Category:Television series by Cosgrove Hall Films]]\n[[Category:Television shows set in Cumbria]]\n[[Category:Television shows set in England]]\n[[Category: Television characters introduced in 1981]]\n", "text_old": "{{EngvarB|date=October 2013}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2013}}\n{{Infobox television\n |show_name = Postman Pat\n |image = Postman-Pat.jpg\n |caption = Postman Pat and his black and white cat, Jess in the original series.\n |genre = [[Children's television series|Children's]], [[animated television series]]\n |creator = [[John Cunliffe (author)|John Cunliffe]]<ref name=BBCLookBack>{{cite news|title=Postman Pat's creator looks back at its conception|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/entertainment-arts-14939816|accessdate=24 June 2014|work=BBC News|date=16 September 2011|quote=The first episode, Postman Pat's Finding Day, was broadcast on 16 September 1981}}</ref>\n |developer = [[Ivor Wood]]\n |writer = [[John Cunliffe (author)|